1 — What is a Locator?
A locator is like a smart “bookmark” for an element.
It doesn’t grab the element immediately — it stores the selector and finds the element when you use it.

📌 Advantages:

Auto-wait for the element to be ready before interacting.

Can be reused multiple times without searching again.

Works even if the DOM changes (if the element reappears).

Cleaner code than query_selector and wait_for_selector.

2 — Basic Example
python
Copy
Edit
from playwright.sync_api import sync_playwright

with sync_playwright() as p:
    browser = p.chromium.launch(headless=False)
    page = browser.new_page()

    page.goto("https://demo.playwright.dev/todomvc")
    
    # Create a locator for the input field
    todo_input = page.locator(".new-todo")
    
    # Type into it
    todo_input.fill("Buy milk")
    todo_input.press("Enter")
    
    # Locator for the first todo item
    first_todo = page.locator(".todo-list li").first
    print("First todo text:", first_todo.text_content())

    browser.close()
💡 Here, todo_input and first_todo are locators, so Playwright will automatically wait until they are available before acting.

3 — When to Use Locators
✅ When interacting with elements (click, fill, check, hover, etc.)
python
Copy
Edit
login_button = page.locator("button#login")
login_button.click()
✅ When reusing the same element multiple times
python
Copy
Edit
search_box = page.locator("input#search")
search_box.fill("Laptops")
page.wait_for_timeout(1000)
search_box.fill("Mobiles")
✅ When you need smart retries for dynamic elements
python
Copy
Edit
dynamic_button = page.locator("button#dynamic")
dynamic_button.click()  # waits until it’s visible & clickable
✅ When working with multiple matches
python
Copy
Edit
# Click the third product from a list
page.locator(".product-item").nth(2).click()

# Loop through all products
products = page.locator(".product-item")
count = products.count()
for i in range(count):
    print(products.nth(i).text_content())
✅ When chaining locators (parent → child)
python
Copy
Edit
card = page.locator(".card").nth(0)
card.locator("button.add-to-cart").click()
4 — Locators vs Immediate Selectors
Wrong way (may fail if element is not instantly available):

python
Copy
Edit
element = page.query_selector("#login")  # finds immediately
element.click()  # fails if not yet rendered
Right way (locator waits automatically):

python
Copy
Edit
page.locator("#login").click()
5 — Power Features of Locators
Filtering by text

python
Copy
Edit
page.locator("button", has_text="Submit").click()
Chaining conditions

python
Copy
Edit
page.locator(".menu").locator("li", has_text="Settings").click()
Built-in actions (all auto-wait):

.click()

.fill()

.press()

.hover()

.check() / .uncheck()

.select_option()

